      {
        "id": "3dd9497d2c82ca7933771cb75409c9bf50d2e308",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-05-16 18:53:20.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nPam, Liam, first is 1) common, 2) drools-pdp, 3) drools-applications, 4) engine.   If you remember we had a cyclical dependency in the past with drools-pdp needing drools-applications, and drools-applications needing drools-pdp libraries we used.   \n\nThis was triggered because of removing the build portion from the docker image.   To resolve this cyclical dependency I had to make drools-pdp agnostic of prepackaging drools-applications deliverables.   \n\nThe solution was to put hooks into external scripts policy_vm_init that then I replaced with the drools-preinstall hook to drive the download of the matching drools-applications zip at installation time.   It also has the good side-effect that the drools-pdp can be used standalone with no applications pre-configured if desired for their own means.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "cf590ac92c8456f9c9b2cd69504cc10de8e334c1",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-05-16 18:53:48.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "c175a1bc3a9fe37823ddebacf5eee8b7e3ec0fa6",
